column30: In May 2016, Nasdaq bolstered its market technology capabilities with the Nasdaq Financial Framework (NFF), a financial infrastructure portfolio that enabled market operators — exchanges, clearinghouses, central securities depositories, alternate trading venues and the like — to develop flexible, tailored solutions for every step in the lifecycle of a trade. It also enabled implementation of new technology. “NFF set us up to be positioned for future trends so we could avoid the near-death experience of PC disruption,” said Brad Peterson, EVP and CTO and CIO at Nasdaq. column30: Mike L., Sr. District Manager, wants to share his sources of inspiration for #BlackHistoryMonth. Where do you find inspiration? "As I think back over my lifetime, I can think of one person that had the biggest impact on my life as a young man and even now as a Leader in WM, my Mother. My father passed away when I was 10-years old. As I think about the struggles, the disappointments, the heartaches, and pain she endured raising 9 kids on her own. This showed me that anything is possible if you hold on to your core values. Seeing her withstand all she went through; she is my Super Woman. This has taught me patience, humility, and perseverance."

column30: Nasdaq achieved its long-standing goal of becoming a global exchange operator when it merged with OMX in 2008 to form the world’s largest global network of exchanges, cementing its place at the top of the worldwide financial tech industry. Combining with OMX instantly gave Nasdaq a massive international presence. The Nasdaq OMX Group listed over 4,000 companies around the world for a total market value of $5.5 trillion. Thanks to the merger, Nasdaq has achieved unprecedented levels of flexibility and scale, which facilitated once unimaginable opportunities for the company, its clients and its investors around the world. Learn more as we celebrate #Nasdaq50: nasdaq50.com

column30: Norfolk Southern is proud to celebrate Black History Month. We recognize Black employees past and present for their contributions to our company and the rail industry – not only in February but throughout the year. A commitment to be a diverse, equitable, and inclusive company is a business imperative for us. Reflecting on Black History Month, CEO Jim Squires notes: “We’ve got to make sure that we systematically dismantle all barriers to advancement, that this is truly a place with opportunity for all. When we focus on DEI, we are focusing on the strength of our business. We are ensuring that the best people will rise to the top and obtain positions of influence, no matter who they are.” This year, Norfolk Southern hosted our first Thoroughbred Trailblazers Awards, paying tribute to Black leaders who are making a positive impact in our communities. Through their work and advocacy, these leaders demonstrated steadfast commitment to help empower and advance opportunities for Blacks and to achieve a more just and equitable society. We are proud to partner with them to make our communities better places to live and work. #blackhistorymonth #community Atlanta Public Schools Chicago Region Environmental and Transportation Efficiency Program (CREATE) Boys & Girls Clubs of America

column6: Kimco Realty Corp. (NYSE: KIM) owns & operates one of North America’s largest publicly traded portfolios of open-air shopping centers.
column30: In celebration of Black History Month, we’re featuring black-owned small businesses in our portfolio. Meet Jackie and Harold owners of Vitality Bowls in Orlando, FL. What inspired you to purchase a franchise such as Vitality Bowls? “We love the idea of not recreating the wheel. Vitality Bowls is an established brand with a network of nationwide franchisees and a proven business model. After researching several business opportunities, Vitality Bowls embraced our lifestyle and our passion with the healthy tasty menu, clean look and feel of the cafe, and transparent kitchen layout.” What makes your business different from other health food establishments? “Vitality Bowls was created out of a strong commitment to bringing health and wellness to every community across the country through fresh, high-quality superfoods. Vitality Bowls specializes in making delicious açaí bowls, which are a thick blend of the açaí berry topped with organic granola and a selection of superfood ingredients. Additional antioxidant-rich menu items include smoothies, fresh juices, soups, salads, and panini. All items on the menu are made fresh to order and in a kitchen designed to avoid cross-contamination of common food allergens. No ingredient fillers such as ice, frozen yogurt, or artificial preservatives are used, giving the purest taste possible to each item.” What are a few ways in which your business demonstrates corporate responsibility in the community? “We were honored to receive the Leader Out of Necessity Award from the West Orange Chamber of Commerce for our support to our first responders and community partners. In 2010 we donated over 1300 smoothies and over 850 healthy meals to Police Stations, Fire Stations, Hospitals, and more! We support with givebacks to local Schools (Free Smoothie Certificates rewarding Students and Teachers), Churches, Charities such as MilesToGo and Matthews Hope. What does it mean to be a black-owned business among the Orlando, Florida community? “We have the opportunity to educate the community on the importance of eating healthy and provide healthy food options to West Orlando.”

column30: Since going public in 2005 under $NDAQ, Nasdaq has gone from being strictly a market provider to something more impactful. "We were a player and had developed our own identity within the industry, but needed independence to fully realize it,” recalled CEO Adena Friedman. In 2001, Nasdaq filed its official application to register as an independent national securities exchange with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), and about a year later, the SEC formally approved Nasdaq’s application to become a registered national securities exchange, which allowed Nasdaq to begin operations as a self-regulatory organization and fully divest itself from the NASD’s control. At long last, Nasdaq was an independent, shareholder-owned company with the freedom to realize its full potential within the financial industry. Learn more as we celebrate #Nasdaq50: nasdaq50.com

Intel and Nasdaq were united by a shared belief in the revolutionary power of technology, and this shared belief keeps their partnership strong today. Intel racked up successes like the world’s first programmable microprocessor, introduced in November 1971, only about a month after its IPO. column30: “Attending Howard was one of the best decisions of my life,” says Executive Director Juneisha Burrowes. “I learned how to change any environment I am in for the better.” Howard University, which is also where the US Vice President Kamala Harris attended, uniquely prepared Burrowes to drive change and open doors for others behind her. She warmly recalls faculty mentors who “were invested in my success and understood the positions I might face in the regular world.” Today as the head of a team protecting our Wealth Management clients from unnecessary risk and co-chair of the Black Employee Network Group (BENG), she plays a similar role at Morgan Stanley—building community, mentoring future leaders, and helping to shape our commitment to diversity and inclusion. Find out more about her experiences as an HBCU graduate and her career since: https://mgstn.ly/3bNhpqw:=:https://www.morganstanley.com/atwork/articles/leading-with-intention?cid=SM_CORP__FACEBOOK_Morgan+Stanley_20210228&linkId=112243766

column30: In 2005, Nasdaq acquired INET, the electronic trading unit of electronic financial firm Instinet. Not only did it offer Nasdaq traders improved performance at a lower cost than the market’s previous platform, but the technology became so highly regarded that Nasdaq started offering it to other markets. It became a lucrative revenue center in its own right, especially after it was combined with the trading technology of another Nasdaq acquisition, OMX. INET’s success signaled a new era of diversification and expansion at Nasdaq. Learn more as we celebrate #Nasdaq50: nasdaq50.com

column6: Great things are ahead of you when your health is ready for them. #StartWithHealthy
column30: Caregiving may be loving and rewarding work, but often leaves little time for self-care. As the caregiver for her husband who has dementia, Humana member Irena knows this all too well. ?????? In 2019, stress was draining her emotionally and driving up her blood pressure. That’s when Irena learned about a class at her Humana Neighborhood Center called “Helping a loved one with dementia” and began working with Humana Neighborhood Center health educator Ada. She listened to Irena’s concerns and suggested healthy, stress-reducing strategies that helped her become the best possible caregiver to her husband—and herself. ?????????? One suggestion from Ada that Irena especially connected to was journaling. Through journal keeping, Irena found new ways to connect with her husband—like watching travel videos of places they’d visited together. After several weeks, both her stress level and blood pressure had gone down. And although COVID-19 has kept her local Humana Neighborhood Center closed, virtual offerings, as well as Ada’s strategies, have continued to help Irena stay healthier. ???? Irena also started collecting positive quotes in her journal, including one she shared with Ada in appreciation: “Health does not always come from medicine. Most of the time it comes from peace of mind, peace in heart, peace of soul. It comes from laughter and love.” ?????? Read more about Humana Neighborhood Centers and Irena’s story at https://humananews.com/news-details/2021/Healthy-habits-for-heart-health/. #humancare #COVID19 It may not be typical to reduce blood pressure by taking the actions Irena did.

column30: We’re celebrating Alex Wright, a customer who is making an important difference in his community. Alex is driven by his deep passion for social justice, and he believes that togetherness, unity, and collaboration will lift Black communities into prosperity. To make an impact, Alex founded African Heritage Food Co-op in 2016 to provide fresh and affordable food, create jobs, and deliver necessary resources to his Buffalo and Niagara Falls communities. Opening a co-op taps the very core of Alex’s beliefs by allowing for him and his community to share ownership and take a collaborative approach to lifting families out of poverty and providing economic opportunity. Their gardens and stores are run in neighborhoods where fresh healthy food hasn’t historically been available and where employees can walk to work, eliminating the need to take money elsewhere and creating an opportunity to keep resources right in the local economy. Learn more about African Heritage Food Co-op on their website: myahfc.com #BlackHistoryMonth #CelebratingCustomers

column30: In June 1982, Nasdaq debuted the National Market System (NMS), offering investors enhanced information and capabilities that were almost as groundbreaking as the existence of Nasdaq itself. The NMS initially included the 49 most actively traded companies listed on Nasdaq. Having so much more data available at a high level of accuracy led to more informed price setting and faster trades, furthering Nasdaq’s original goal of bringing greater fairness and efficiency to the markets. Learn more as we celebrate #Nasdaq50: nasdaq50.com

column30: As we round out #HeartMonth, we are reminded that the hearts of healthcare heroes show up daily to advocate for the best care possible for our patients. The big hearts of doctors, nurses and other healthcare workers across HCA Healthcare are the reason that patients like ten-month-old Clark are thriving today. “Through a lot of little miracles, we ended up at Rocky Mountain Hospital for Children,” said Clark’s mom. At one month of age, Clark had complex heart surgery at the Denver, Colorado hospital. Clark’s mom is grateful for the expert care, gentle hugs and friendships made with the hospital staff during her son’s three month stay. Thank you to our caregivers who give their all to serve Clark and all of our tiniest, mightiest patients! #HealthierTomorrows

column6: Kansas City Southern (KCS) is a railroad that serves the central and south central U.S. and northeastern and central Mexico and the port cities of Lázaro Cárdenas, Tampico and Veracruz.
column30: Last week’s weather took much of the south by surprise with below freezing temperatures, snow and ice in places not accustomed to it. This extreme winter weather impacted much of the KCS network from Missouri south to Mississippi, Louisiana and Texas and even northern Mexico, grinding some aspects of normal life to a halt with ice-covered and closed roads, power and water outages, fuel station shortages and closures, and empty store shelves. While facing challenges with their own homes and families, many employees worked tirelessly to help their fellow KCS employees, employees from other railroads, and customers to help maintain and restore vital services to customers and the greater community. KCS had an all-hands on deck approach to clean switches and walkways, maintain equipment, facilities and critical IT infrastructure, and provide alternative and temporary accommodations for rest where normal resources were not available. “As proven many times before, when weather impacts the operation, KCS people do whatever must be done to restore and maintain vitally important service to customers and the greater community,” said KCS executive vice president and chief operating officer Jeff Songer. “When looking at the many heroic actions that were taken and personal sacrifices made, and knowing there were many more unreported, it paints a picture of the pride, dedication and commitment employees have to KCS’ vision and values. Thank you for your service.” KCS employees are essential and resilient. We salute you. #KCS #KansasCitySouthern #Resilient #Essential

column30: ?? Last week we shared threads to offer more understanding into intermittent outages & what will happen to your bill next month. Today we want to empower you with a thread of 10 ways to save and become more energy efficient. 1. You can't always predict the highs and lows of Midwest weather ?? ??? ?? ??? ? , but you can average out your monthly bill with our Average Payment Plan. https://www.evergy.com/manage-account/billing/payment-options/average-payment-plan 2. You can get rewarded with rate discounts ?? when you shift your weekday energy use to off-peak times, like after 8 p.m. This means running your dishwasher and washer and dryer during off-peak hours. Eligible Missouri customers can learn more about this plan here: https://www.evergy.com/manage-account/rate-information/plan-options/time-of-use-plan 3. Enroll in our Thermostat Program. We’re currently offering the ecobee3 lite for free to eligible Missouri customers. As part of the program, you can participate in Energy Savings Events (which you can choose to opt out of). These events help manage energy usage on select days of extreme heat when everyone is cranking up their air conditioner. https://www.evergy.com/landing/easy-to-install-smart-thermostats 4. During the winter ?? lowering your settings by 1 degree for at least eight hours will save you about 1% on your energy bill. During the summer, each degree you set your thermostat above 75 degrees cuts your cooling costs by about 3%. 5. Incandescent bulbs use more energy that LED bulbs. If you replace them with high efficiency fixtures, they’ll use 90% less energy and last 15 times longer. You can also take advantage of natural light by opening shades and blinds, reducing the need for electric lighting. 6. Invest in smart power strips. ?? ?? A smart strip can detect when devices are in standby or powered off. They’ll cut off power to devices in standby or powered off to save energy. Allows a person to set it and forget it. 7. Standby power loss accounts for as much as 20% of your bill. Leaving items plugged in like your ?? cell phone charger and cable box will use power even when you’re not using them. 8. If you’re a gamer or a parent of a gamer ?? , know that your gaming console uses 10x more power than a tablet or laptop. Make sure to unplug it when it’s not in use. 9. If you wash clothes in cold water, it can save you about 50 cents per load. That adds up over a month. 10. You want to change your furnace filter every three months and also clean and change your air filters monthly. This will allow air to properly flow and ensure that your furnace and air conditioner are working at peak efficiency. ?? ?? You can learn more about ways to save on our website: https://www.evergy.com/ways-to-save/resources/energy-savings/energy-saving-tips?custType=R

column30: To close out #NationalEngineersWeek, we're highlighting sisters Catie and Carah who have a shared passion for engineering and STEM. Catie is a technical sales representative at our company and Carah is an incoming TI intern. Both participated in the Opportunity Research Scholars Program (ORS) at Georgia Tech, which is supported by TI. “Being involved in ORS was an empowering experience for me," said Catie. "While in ORS, I was involved in the Haiti Solar Project. The main goal of the project was to create a modular, scalable solar home system to allow people living in Haiti access to light and a USB port to charge their phone, while also easily scaling as power demand increases. Having the opportunity to work on this research got me excited about the impact I could have as an engineer." column30: In 2014 my mom was diagnosed with breast cancer. It was caught early, but she had to undergo very harsh chemotherapy and radiation during her battle. I am proud to announce she is a six-year breast cancer survivor! Three years after her initial breast cancer diagnosis, in 2017, she was rushed to the emergency room for what she thought was an asthma attack. She was having a heart attack caused by reduced functioning of the heart from the harsh type of chemo she underwent for her breast cancer. First responders, nurses, and doctors saved my mom. Supporting the American Heart Association is a no brainer for me. Cherish and support even the smallest victories in the fight against heart related illnesses. - Heather Raney, Rockford, IL

LIVE | Day 5 of our #COVID19 #VaccineSymposium

We are very excited for the final day of the #COVID19 #VaccineSymposium! Joining our moderator Dr. Marc Grodman, of the Columbia University Vagelos College of Physicians and Surgeons and CEO of Genosity Inc., are:
- a welcome from Ira Katznelson, PhD – Interim Provost, Columbia University in the City of New York
- a keynote by Moncef Slaoui, MS, PhD – Former Director, Operation Warp Speed, @U.S. Department of Defense (DoD)
- a keynote by Ezekiel Emanuel, MD, MSc, PhD – Vice Provost, Global Initiatives, University of Pennsylvania
- Margaret Hamburg, MD – Foreign Secretary, National Academy of Medicine
- Stanley M. Bergman – Chairman of the Board and CEO, @Henry Schein, Inc.
- John Nkengasong, MSc, PhD – Director, Africa CDC
- a journalist's perspective from Kai Kupferschmidt – Contributing Correspondent, Science Magazine
- closing remarks from Stanley Plotkin, MD – Emeritus Professor of Pediatrics, Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania

column30: “This Black History Month is different. This is an opportunity for us to reflect on action that we’re taking based on an experience the entire country had last year. We have learned much already, and we need to continue to learn – that’s true for all of us – and having actionable items to take from that is critical.” – Haig Ariyan, President of Alex Brown and Head of Global Wealth Solutions This week, Raymond James leaders reflected on what they have learned, given the events of cultural unrest that have transpired over the last year, and where they see the firm going in the future. Executives Paul Shoukry, Jim Bunn, Kim Jenson and Haig Ariyan talked about the cultural initiatives that have been prioritized throughout the company over the past year – including actively supporting employee inclusion networks, proactive and purposeful conversations with coworkers and the various recruiting initiatives to attract diverse new talent. Although we have made progress with these initiatives, we at Raymond James recognize there is much more to do. #BlackHistoryMonth #RJInclusion

column30: “Protecting the joy, vulnerability, and innocence of Black boys has been a huge part of this generation’s representation of masculinity. We want to preserve the wonder and adventure of Black boys exploring their emotional landscapes of care, play and introspection.” - Bradford Young In this chapter of “Black History Written By,” Academy award-winning cinematographer and director Bradford Young tells the stories of a chef, snowboarder and musicians who embody their own version of Black Boy Joy as they write Black History every day. Edouardo J. honors the recipes of his ancestors and creates new ones at his two restaurants in Seattle, Salare Restaurant and JuneBaby. On the slopes of Colorado, flyinbrianrice is on track to be the first Black U.S. snowboarder in the Winter Olympics. Black Violin is a classical, hip hop duo that is changing the perception of Black men, and the violin, through their music. “Black Boy Joy” Directed by Bradford Young Cinematography by Shawn Peters Edited by Marc Thomas Photography by Fred Agho, Jamel Shabazz, Justin French & Stephanie Mei-Ling Music by Black Violin Produced by Nanette Nelms Discover how the Black community is using Facebook and Instagram to share Black Boy Joy at https://about.fb.com/community.:=:https://about.fb.com/community/

column30: “As a black man in America, as a person of color, I knew my son Solomon was always going to have to explain himself from a race perspective because of the color of his skin. I thought, what better way to make a book that will help him understand himself, and for me, as a way to share about my story and myself.” A Kids Book About is a book collection tackling important, empowering, and challenging topics - from racism to cancer to bullying - that can be difficult for parents to explain to children. When Jelani Memory, the series' creator, put them on Instagram, a support community of parents grew - making us grown-ups feel less alone in these tough conversations. To see more Community Voices videos visit: https://fb.me/CommunityVoicesVideos:=:https://www.facebook.com/watch/108824017345866/1257355224623448

column30: Dr. Marc Regis Hannah (1956-Present) Whether you’ve heard his name or seen his work, it’s likely you have enjoyed the cinematic experience of Dr. Marc Regis Hannah. Dr. Hannah is a renowned electrical engineer and one of the innovative powerhouses behind Silicon Graphics, Inc. (SGI), a highly influential computer graphics firm that specializes in software and hardware for cutting-edge 3D illustrations and effects. Hannah developed the 3D special effects systems used widely in movies such as Terminator 2 (1991) and Beauty and the Beast (1991). His work is also used in aerospace and biotech engineering laboratories across the world. Today, we celebrate the notable accomplishments of Dr. Marc Regis Hannah.

column30: We're back with another Cabot farmer takeover for #FarmloveFriday -- and we can't believe February is almost over ?? This week photos and captions by Joanna Lidback at The Farm at Wheeler Mountain in Vermont. So without further ado: "Hi! I’m Joanna Lidback and together with my husband Adam, and our three kids, we operate The Farm at Wheeler Mountain in the Northeast Kingdom of Vermont. Happy to be here with you today as I share some images of our farm with you. We don’t stop to take family photos very often, so this is a little dated, but we're mostly the same. The snow pic is a recent shot of Wheeler Mountain, which is what how we got our farm name. This notable peak stands sentinel over our farm and is seen often in many of our photos. Also, doesn’t our red tractor look so festive in this picture?" And a similar shot in the summer! From Joanna: "They say the summer make the winters worth it up here, and I would add the spring (sugaring season) and fall foliage does too. We are counting down the days until the snow and mud disappear and the cows can go roam our pastures again.” Where can I see *more* great photos? Well, glad you asked. #FarmloveFriday is also over on Instagram (see our stories!), Twitter, and Pinterest. Join us. Ask questions. Feel the love. ?? ?? ?? ?? ?? ?? ?? ??

column30: “I can no longer treat you. I don't feel comfortable.” In honor of #RareDiseaseDay, we asked Ashley P., who lives with #BehcetsDisease, to tell us about her journey. This is what she had to say: “After countless months of visits to the emergency room and working with my primary care physician, OB-GYN and an infectious disease doctor, I was met with this dead-end phrase while speaking with a rheumatologist. My journey with Behçet’s Disease started when I was 19, and I’m still on it. I was misdiagnosed repeatedly, and I knew we weren’t getting to the root of the issue. So, after hearing that disheartening phrase from the rheumatologist, from then on, I had to become my own quarterback. I found my own doctors, did my own research, purchased literature on Behçet’s Disease, learned about it that way. It took me three years and over 30 doctors to actually get the correct diagnosis. I was told I was crazy, my symptoms are psychosomatic, and I'm causing this to myself. Now I know that my symptoms, like oral ulcers, were due to Behçet’s Disease, a rare, chronic, inflammatory condition that can affect multiple systems in the body and can manifest itself in a variety of symptoms. I had to be my own advocate. I had to fight. Since then, I've learned to slow down and take it easy. I can't compare myself now to my old body. In some ways, this journey has given me the mental strength that I have today. I always, always tell someone going through the same struggle to look for outside support groups, places like social media, that’s where I found my support. If you ever find someone that's near you connect with them, make friends with them, and you'll feel less alone.” National Organization for Rare Disorders, Inc. (NORD) American Behcet's Disease Association - ABDA Vasculitis Foundation

column30: American Heart Month is deeply important to me because five years ago my husband had quadruple bypass surgery. While at work one Monday, he became winded very quickly and began experiencing pain in his middle back and shoulder area. After encouragement from a colleague, he went to urgent care. By that Friday he had surgery, and according to doctors, thank goodness he did. He had two arteries clogged over 90%, one about 60% and the other about 30%. The lower portion of his heart had not been receiving blood. The doctors said had he not gone to the urgent care he very likely would have had a major heart attack. - Ami Whelan, Cayce, SC

Green leaves painted at the entrance represent an eco-friendly lifestyle. A mural called “Flowing Colors” depicts colorful apartment buildings. column6: Empowering people who serve the public.
column30: In 1960, six-year-old Ruby Bridges walked to school, accompanied by federal marshals, to become the first African American student to integrate the all-white William Frantz Elementary School in Louisiana. Ostracized and threatened with violence, she never missed a day of school that year and eventually went on to business school to study travel and tourism. In 1999, she established The Ruby Bridges Foundation to end racism and promote tolerance, respect, and appreciation of differences through education. In 2000, she was made an honorary deputy marshal in a ceremony in Washington, D.C. When we reflect on the difficult moments of the past, we can face the difficult moments of today armed with knowledge, compassion, and action to ensure these events are not repeated. Read more about Ruby Bridges: https://bit.ly/3aVLiWu:=:https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/ruby-bridges?utm_campaign=coschedule&utm_source=facebook_page&utm_medium=Tyler Technologies, Inc. We encourage you to continue to research, learn from, and be inspired by these and other powerful pioneers beyond this month's reflection. #BHM21 #PublicSectorHeroes

column30: Gregg Moore, Business Banking Relationship Manager, celebrates Lunar New Year as a way to connect his daughter to her culture. In 2015, Gregg and his wife traveled to China to adopt Ellie, now 10. “When we adopted Ellie, she was an orphan and too young to have a real understanding of her heritage, so our Lunar New Year celebration serves as an opportunity for us all to learn more about China.” Gregg and his wife spent two weeks in China to complete the adoption process. During that time, they immersed themselves in the culture, learning about Chinese history and sampling traditional foods so that they could share their knowledge with Ellie. “We celebrated our first Lunar New Year a few months after we brought Ellie home, so it serves as a sort of anniversary of when she completed our family.” Gregg says that since they don't have much extended family nearby, their celebration plans haven't changed much from prior years. “It will just be the four of us, small and intimate.” To create a festive environment, the family decorates the house with Chinese lanterns. They enjoy dishes from their favorite local Chinese restaurant which they eat with chopsticks purchased in China. He also gives the children educational books about Lunar New Year and small cash gifts in red envelopes per the tradition. #LunarNewYear #CommunityBank
column33: Gregg Gre Moore Business Banking Relationship Manage Buffalo,NY

column30: With customers continuing their cleanup and repair efforts throughout our service area as a result of the recent severe winter weather, we want to share these important natural gas safety tips to help keep everyone safe: - Don’t place debris near your natural gas meter during the clean-up process. The equipment used to collect it can cause damage to the meter and a hazardous situation. - If you suspect a natural gas leak, leave the area immediately on foot and tell others to do the same. When safely away, report the leak by calling 911 and the CenterPoint Energy emergency hotline. - When doing outdoor cleanup or repairs that require digging, remember to always Call Before You Dig by dialing 811. Find additional safety tips at https://www.centerpointenergy.com/en-us/residential/safety/weather-safety

column30: 15-year-old Wyoming teenager, KyZaia Jones, beat the odds after being electrocuted while helping to save his friends from a car accident. Airlifted six weeks ago to HCA Healthcare’s Swedish Medical Center's Burn and Reconstructive Center in Colorado, KyZaia sustained burns on nearly 50% of his body, almost all of them third-degree. KyZaia's burns were treated with skin grafts and spray-on skin cells, and he leaned on his faith, family and caregivers as he fought for his life. "From the moment Ky was admitted he showed a strength that could only be described as inspiring,” said Swedish Medical Center nurse, Amanda Hergenreder. “When his family arrived that night, his first questions for them were about his friends from the accident. When he was told that the shock he sustained kept his friend from being electrocuted, he told his parents that he'd do it again. That strength never wavered even through bad days and tough situations. I am proud to have been part of his recovery.” #WATCH as KyZaia shares his incredible story and is met with a sendoff made for a hero from his extended hospital family ? https://cbsloc.al/3uu8zGR:=:https://denver.cbslocal.com/2021/02/22/teenager-electrocuted-swedish-burns-wyoming/ #CareLikeFamily #BurnAwareness
column34: Wyoming Teenager, Electrocuted While Helping Others, Leaves Swedish Medical Center After 6 Weeks

column30: “Portrait of Brian” by Sabl? S. & Sabrina C. flyinbrianrice is writing Black History as he sets out to be the first Black U.S. snowboarder in the Winter Olympics. “When it comes to snowboarding, people don’t see you for your Blackness. It never comes down to what’s under the mask, the helmet, or the coat,” explains Brian R. Jr. “People see you for what you can do on the board.” Brian R. Jr. shares new tricks and jumps on Facebook daily. He’s setting an example for the next generation by changing the perception of what a snowboarder can be. “Black Boy Joy—when I hear it, I automatically see a young African American doing what they love,” says Brian R. Jr. “Not because somebody made them or not because it’s the right thing to do, but because that’s what they love to do—it’s something they created for themselves, it’s something that makes them happy.” Discover more stories about Black Boy Joy at https://about.fb.com/community.:=:https://about.fb.com/community/

column30: We are so proud to be a founding partner of the Ad Council's COVID-19 vaccine education initiative.
column35:
In partnership with the COVID Collaborative, today we are proud to announce the creative platform for our COVID-19 vaccine education initiative, “It’s Up To You,” the largest and most critical communications effort in our nation’s history.

Black and Hispanic communities have been hit especially hard by the pandemic, and due to systemic inequities, there is greater hesitancy—our research indicates that only 40% of Black and Hispanic individuals say they feel confident enough to make a decision about vaccination. 

With many distinct campaigns under one umbrella, and a special focus on reaching communities of color, “It’s Up To You” takes an empathetic approach that reaffirms it’s understandable to have questions and that getting educated about the vaccines is a key step toward getting back to the moments and people we miss. To get the latest information about COVID-19 vaccines, visit GetVaccineAnswers.org.

column30: Garrett Morgan was an automotive pioneer and inventor who is best known for his contributions to the development of the traffic light. In 1922, Morgan filed a patent for a traffic light with three signals. By having a third position between “Stop” and “Go”, Morgan’s signal helped prevent auto collisions which were prevalent with earlier signals. As Black History Month comes to a close – and each time we hit the road, we’ll be thinking of Garrett Morgan and all of the other Black pioneers who helped shape the automotive industry as we know it today. #GetInTheZone

column30: Meet Da’Nielle Green, a Production Engineer working out of our West Texas office in Midland. Da’Nielle says Black History Month means “embracing who I am not only just during the month of February but every day. I truly honor and thank those who paved a way for not only me but countless others. These are women and men with tremendous character, courage, dedication, commitment and perseverance.” A graduate of Tuskegee University, a historically Black university (HBCU), Da’Nielle says the experience gave her “a true sense of culture, pride, and confidence” while also successfully preparing her for her professional career. We appreciate the valuable contributions that Da’Nielle makes to the Occidental Delaware Basin team and are proud to recruit from HBCUs like Tuskegee University as part of our culture of Diversity, Inclusion and Belonging. Learn more at https://lnkd.in/dxuKiph:=:https://www.oxy.com/Careers/DiversityInclusionBelonging/Pages/default.aspx and follow us on Instagram @WeAreOxy to learn more about Da’Nielle and her colleagues #WeAreOxy #BlackHistoryMonth

Magic Genie in a Bottle!

How does it work? Hydrogen peroxide is added to the flask and a small amount of manganese dioxide is dropped into the flask which causes the hydrogen peroxide to rapidly decompose into water and oxygen gas. column30: It’s Throwback Thursday! Robert L. Milloy joined the Southern Railway in 1950. He grew up in Laurel, Mississippi, and—after a short stint working in his uncle’s funeral home—enlisted in the U. S. Army at age 20 and served in World War II. In 1947, he married his wife, Lorene, and settled in Birmingham, Alabama. Milloy worked for the railroad as a laborer, a hostler, and a fireman before becoming a locomotive engineer. In 1972, when this photograph was taken, his duties included keeping trains moving between Birmingham, Alabama, and Atlanta, Georgia. Hardworking and dedicated railroad employees—then and now—make things happen. Behind every Norfolk Southern train is an extensive network of track and terminals, a fleet of sophisticated locomotives and freight cars, and a team of employees who work around the clock to provide safe and reliable rail transportation. Railroaders like Robert L. Milloy have always kept the trains rolling. #respect #blackhistorymonth

column35:
**A Message from Honoring Heroes Contest Prize Co-Sponsor - Cabot Creamer Co-operative**

Create the Good knew the farm families who own Cabot Creamery Co-operative would be the perfect partners in the Honoring Heroes Contest because they have always believed in the value of hard work and neighbors helping neighbors. Because the contest shines the spotlight on dedicated Veterans who continue to serve our nation, Cabot was honored to be a part of this program. 
 
Cabot farmer Jenni Tilton-Flood puts it this way: "We hear the word "Heroes" a lot these days but what we don't hear enough is THANK YOU. So thank you, from my farm family to the winners for the commitment and continued dedication to duty, service, leadership, and inspiration your selflessness and compassion provides for all of us. Our communities, our Nation, and our world looks to Veterans like you who continue to embody the best of what we can be and achieve. Our farmer gratitude knows no limits for your deeds and work.” 
 
Along with the folks at Cabot, we send our thanks and gratitude to all the Veterans who inspire us with the passion and dedication to making their communities better, one volunteer hour at a time.

#createthegood #cabotcreamery #veterans

column30: Meet Randall Barnes, one of Alliant Energy’s talented engineers! Randall has been working at Alliant Energy for nine months. He also interned with us during the summer of 2019. An AP physics teacher in high school introduced Randall to engineering. Once he entered college, he joined the National Society of Black Engineers (NSBE), which further cemented his engineering career goals. Randall said the reason he chose Alliant Energy for both his internship and job had a lot to do with the welcoming environment. Randall said he believes Alliant Energy’s workers truly demonstrate the company’s values. “At Alliant Energy, every day is an opportunity to learn and improve upon what I do,” said Randall. Randall is an Engineer I in the Delivery System Planning department for the Burlington, Keokuk, Ottumwa and Washington zones. His primary function is to provide long-range plans and recommendations for the electrical distribution system to accommodate growth and increase system reliability and robustness. Engineering is special to Randall because he believes an engineer’s core purpose is to create solutions to various problems. He said every project is like a new canvas to work with. “Behind a strong community is a strong electrical grid; most of us depend heavily on power,” said Randall. “I feel that my work helps contribute to creating and maintaining that healthy backbone, so customers and communities can flip the light switch with confidence!” Randall’s advice to aspiring engineers is to have a positive attitude, embrace challenges and have an open mind toward each situation because life’s circumstances are not all homogenous. Thank you for all you do for us, Randall! We are lucky to have you as a part of our team at Alliant Energy! #PoweringBeyond #Iamenergy #Eweek2021 #EngineersWeek

column30: Meet Connie Maluwelmeng, one of Alliant Energy’s talented engineers! In 2015, Connie started at Alliant Energy as an intern with Delivery System Planning West and was able to extend her internship through her last school year. In 2016, she then started full-time with the same team following her graduation. Growing up on the island of Guam was what sparked her inspiration to become an engineer. She said she was especially interested in how the citizens of Guam could become less reliant on imported diesel and use more of their own surrounding resources to power the island. After a Navy recruiter came to her class one day and discussed the various engineering roles in the Navy, the rest was history. Connie chose to intern and work at Alliant Energy because of the company culture. She said she enjoys the various people she gets to collaborate with and learn from. Connie and her team model their distribution electric grid to identify any potential issues today (thermal, voltage, etc.) and issues and growth that we may see in the future. They then work with the rest of the engineering teams and their operations teams (including internal teams and external utility partners) to identify solutions to be able to provide customers with exceptional service. Being challenged every day, thinking of ways to utilize new technologies and collaborating with her team members are all the best parts about being an engineer, according to Connie. Not only does she embrace our company values in the workplace by actively trying to make things better, do the right thing and act for tomorrow, she also embraces these values in her personal life by giving back to the community. Connie regularly tries to hit 150 volunteer hours every year. A lot of her time is spent with the Cedar Rapids Public Library and the United Way of East Central Iowa. Thank you for all you do for us, Connie! We are lucky to have you as a part of our team at Alliant Energy! #PoweringBeyond #Iamenergy #EWeek2021 #EngineersWeek

column6: Our mission is to serve patients with a cutting-edge, science-based approach. The #PeopleofAmgen make this mission happen. #WeAreBiotech
column30: In honor of #BlackHistoryMonth, we asked David Elion, Senior Associate Scientist in Oncology, to share how his life journey – including his time in academia and as a professional musician – helped shape and support his career in science. Here’s what he had to say: My journey to science was not a straightforward one. Before graduate school, I actually had a professional life working in music, which is what I studied as an undergrad at Brown University. As a violinist, I gigged and taught middle school, and I also worked in artist management and publishing. Music teaches you the value of patience, consistency, and collaboration, all things I bring to my work as a scientist now. Although I enjoyed teaching and making music, I ultimately decided to pursue my other vocational interest, science, in the hope of making a meaningful contribution to cancer research. During my Ph.D. work at Vanderbilt University, I studied breast tumor immunology. Although I found the academic work both fascinating and rewarding, I decided to pivot to a career in biotech to have a practical and more direct impact on patients’ lives. #wearebiotech At Amgen, I work in the biomarker discovery group, looking for new therapeutic targets for medicines. Currently, I feel as though I align with our core value “Be Ethical” the most. Being new, I try my best to be as transparent as possible with my boss and team about how I conduct research and my scientific results. Black History Month has always been a time for me to reflect on my community’s culture and history, and how it has shaped this country. While I personally celebrate Black culture and history year-round, in February, I make a more concerted effort to participate in community focused events and presentations where I live.
column33: "Before graduate school, actually had a professional life working in music, which is what /studied as an undergrad at Brown University." "Music teaches you the value of patience, consistency, and collaboration, all things bring to my work as a scientist now."

column34: CVS Health Live: Addressing COVID-19 Vaccine Hesitancy
column35:
According to the National Institutes of Health, 75 to 80 percent of Americans must receive the COVID-19 vaccine for the U.S. to reach herd immunity. And while news around a COVID-19 vaccine has brought much optimism to the broader American population, it’s also brought distrust in the health care system to the forefront of the conversation – one that is not a new issue within the Black community. In this episode of CVS Health Live, our expert panel will address important aspects of this issue, including understanding the role of racism and historical injustices in present-day distrust, and the steps that health care providers and the industry can take to improve trust in the COVID-19 vaccines and in the health care system overall. 

Moderated by David Casey, Senior Vice President and Chief Diversity Officer, CVS Health, this episode will feature perspectives from Georges Benjamin, M.D., Executive Director, American Public Health Association, and Mercilla Ryan-Harris, M.P.H., Co-Founder, BLKHLTH.

column6: Kimberly-Clark and our brands are passionate about providing you with the essentials for a better life. Learn more about us at www.kimberly-clark.com
column30: We have a goal to reduce our global plastic footprint by 50% by 2030. In the UK, our Kleenex®, Huggies®, and Andrex® brands are driving forward with this ambitious goal by innovating to eliminate plastics from their products and packaging. With the Kleenex® 'Every Step Counts' program, the brand removed all plastic collars from boxes in the UK and introduced 30% post-consumer recycled content (PCR) in its multipack compact boxes. As part of the ‘Tiniest Footprint’ program, Huggies® introduced a new biodegradable baby wipe in its Pure range and reduced plastic content in all of its wipes, as well as introducing 30% PCR in its DryNites® packaging. Andrex® committed to a “Greener PawPrint” by removing all plastic handles from wrapped packs, introducing 30% PCR in its packaging, and making the packaging recyclable on flushable wipes. These sustainability programs in total have eliminated more than 470 tons of plastic per year and removed more than 660 tons of virgin plastic per year in the UK. Learn more about our Plastics Footprint program here: http://spr.ly/6180HY1O0:=:https://www.kimberly-clark.com/esg/smallest-footprint/plastics

column30: To wrap up our celebration of #BlackHistoryMonth, we spoke with Claudia Chery, the Digital Marketing Manager for Ametek Brookfield and a member of AMETEK’s African American Business Council, which helps ensure all employees at the company are valued and their voices heard. Q: What does Black History Month mean to you? A: It celebrates the richness of African American heritage, culture, languages, and art as well as the scientific and financial contributions to our society — and so much more. It’s acknowledging that African American achievements are not only woven into the fabric of our nation’s history and culture, but also the foundation for so many things we may take for granted now. It’s taking a moment to reflect on how critical African American citizens are to our global community. It’s pausing to honor the many sacrifices African Americans have made that allow me to be where I am now. Q: Who are your Black History heroes? · Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. · Maya Angelou · Michelle and Barack Obama
column33: AMETEK CELEBRATES BLACK HISTORY MONTH CLAUDIA CHERY Digital Marketing Manager AMETEK Brookfield "It's "It's acknowledging that African American achievements are not only woven into the fabric of our nation's history and culture, but also the foundation for so many things we may take for granted now. column30: She can do it! 94-year-old Mae Krier's pioneering spirit means she jumps in when her community needs help. She rolled up her sleeves as a Rosie the Riveter at Boeing in Washington while still a teenager during WWII. Later she lobbied to ensure all Rosies were recognized with a Congressional Gold Medal. When her community needed her again, Mae got busy sewing thousands of Rosie-inspired COVID masks. Now, we're honoring Mae's service to country by flying one of her creations on Starliner's Orbital Flight Test-2. column30: “Portrait of Black Violin” by Sabl? S. & Sabrina C. Kevin M. and Will B. are writing Black History as the classical, hip hop duo behind Black Violin. “The violin is a weapon. It's how I disarm people that think they know who I am if I walk through the door,” says Kevin M. “Black Violin changed the perception of what a Black man can do, and what a violin is capable of.” Both Kevin M. and Will B. are classically trained musicians, that flipped their craft on its head by integrating hip hop into their music. “I think the war was just ignoring that voices— people saying that you have to do classical music a certain way,” explains Will B. “We are hip-hop. Hip-hop is about expressing yourself.” Together, they bring Black Boy Joy to Instagram through their music, which is redefining the power of the violin every time they play. “I’m not a classical musician, I’m just an artist,” says Will B. “Our music—Black music—is everything. Every genre is Black music.” Discover more about Black Boy Joy at https://about.fb.com/community.:=:https://about.fb.com/community/

column30: Last summer, and three years into his AIG career, 26-year-old Connor Weaver received an unexpected opportunity to serve as the reverse mentor for David McElroy, AIG’s CEO for General Insurance and Co-Chair of AIG’s Executive Diversity Council. During their initial conversation, Connor offered candid observations about the company’s Diversity, Equity and Inclusion progress, helping David to become an even better ally. And he says the experience equally benefits him. Being able to connect with an experienced executive teaches Connor valuable lessons about leadership and effective communication, skills that he now applies to his role as a Financial Lines Senior Underwriter. This has given him the confidence to more clearly advise his broker partners and valued clients through a challenging market environment. He’s also paying these lessons forward. As President of the Georgia Black Professionals & Allies Employee Resource Group (ERG), one of seven such groups globally at AIG, Connor helps to organize professional development programs that advance the careers of his Black colleagues. In Connor’s wide-ranging discussion with David, the two covered topics like networking and their love of professional football. And they also spoke openly about diversity in the workplace, specifically on how to create a more inclusive culture at AIG. “Through our conversation, I learned the importance of active listening.” As an ERG leader, Connor says he tries to model this behavior and that by really listening to the concerns of his ERG members and the rest of the AIG community, he’s building lasting relationships that will cultivate a more diverse, equitable and inclusive workplace. For Connor, the opportunity to build a relationship with one of AIG’s most senior leaders is helping to shape his insurance career, and is a benefit he didn’t expect when he first started at AIG. “The fact that we can have an honest conversation makes it all the more worthwhile. As a result, I’ve started to become an ally to others and am seeking out more mentorships.” #Diversity #Inclusion #LifeatAIG

Lydia spearheaded NiHao, a contemporary Chinese restaurant whose menu features collaborative Chinese cuisine by chefs Peter, Lisa Chang as well as Pichet Ong. Opening in the midst of pandemic, their a la carte menu features to-go friendly dishes with environmentally friendly packaging. column30: “There are so many reasons that a volcano might impact a person,” says Dr. Kayla Iacovino. Even if you’re nowhere near a ??, like in the middle of a ??field, a large eruption can impact your daily life in small, but noticeable ways like an increase in product prices because it’s coming from overseas, or a food item you can’t get because the crop that year was decimated by an eruption. In her role as a Jacobs Experimental Petrologist and Volcanologist at NASA's Johnson Space Center, Kayla uses a combination of fieldwork, laboratory experiments and thermodynamic modeling to better understand the inner workings of crustal volcanic systems, and when and why catastrophic eruptions occur. See why they call her “The Volcano Trekker”: http://jcob.co/liCW50DEIJz:=:https://www.jacobs.com/newsroom/news/celebrating-engineers-week-2021-jacobs-teammates-challenging-today-reinventing?utm_source=social&utm_medium=facebook&utm_term=6cd27d49-78a5-4a1e-83fc-90bcb046f140&utm_content=&utm_campaign=news-release #eweek2021

column30: Wabtec is electrifying bus fleets! The city of Edmonton (Alberta, Canada) successfully integrated 40 electric buses into their fleet last year. Accepted by operators, passengers and maintenance personnel, ebus evaluations confirmed a low total cost of ownership & maintenance with superior on-road performance - even during cold winters. The buses are charged utilizing twenty-two ceiling mounted pantographs from Wabtec that can charge up to 900kW, are fast and require limited space. Watch the automatic charging operation. When complete, charging stops and the pantograph returns to the upward, stowed position. The same ‘safe’ position is reached in case of power failure only by mechanical means. These inverted pantographs are connected to rapid chargers, which store the electrical energy during off-peak hours when power is less expensive. #WabtecBusSolutions #chargingpanto #publictransport #Ebus #emobility #chargingstation #fastcharging #WeAreWabtec

column30: Last week, we began our public sector hero series in celebration of Black History Month with a look at Barbara Jordan and John Mercer Langston's life and inspiration. Read about our next featured historical figure below. After witnessing an accident between a horse-drawn carriage and an automobile, Garrett Morgan dreamed up a three-position traffic signal that was patented in 1923. The invention saved lives in a time when horses, cars, and people all shared the roads in a rather chaotic way. Garrett also received a patent in 1912 for his safety hood and smoke protector, a precursor to the gas mask we use today. He created the hood to enhance the safety of firefighters and rescue crews. The invention earned him the first prize at the Second International Exposition of Safety and Sanitation in New York City. Read more about Garrett Morgan: https://bit.ly/2Nwg1QY:=:https://www.biography.com/inventor/garrett-morgan?utm_campaign=coschedule&utm_source=facebook_page&utm_medium=Tyler Technologies, Inc. #BHM21 #PublicSectorHeroes

column30: Scrum Master Craig Staszak has attended Lunar New Year festivals all over the world: Hong Kong, Toronto, Australia, Vietnam, Korea, and Thailand to name a few. Although most have been cancelled this year due to the pandemic, he and his family will still celebrate at home. Although not a part of his own heritage, Craig says that he and his wife grew up with a heavy Asian influence. They have friends and family who are Buddhist Taoist, and they celebrate Lunar New Year in their honor. This year, Craig has decorated his home with lanterns and wall hangings that represent the upcoming year’s zodiac animal, the ox. “After exchanging the traditional red envelopes, we start cooking and that lasts for 10 days,” he said. “As my family is mostly vegan or vegetarian, we tend to have bags of vegetables, spices and noodles and every day we try to prepare dishes from different cultures.” Between cooking and eating, the family takes breaks to sing and play music. “At the end of each day we put money in a glass and shake it while eating to signify a prosperous year ahead. Full bellies, Full wallet.” Craig’s dedication to Lunar New Year is more than skin deep. “Each year, I expand on my original animal tattoos. I have a large ox with a yin yang on my back and this year I’m planning to add color to the yin yang.”
column33: 2021 Û wish everyone inner peace, health, and prosperity." Craig Staszak Scrum Master Buffalo, NY

column30: Tia D., Sr. Legal Counsel, has been with WM for more than 13 years and shared some of her experiences with us. "As an African American woman, it has been meaningful and impactful to have people in leadership demonstrate an interest in my career development and provide me with opportunities to work on and lead projects and recognize my efforts at the company. Part of this was tied to me taking risks in opening up to leadership in my group by sharing my views, goals and even concerns after being encouraged by them to do so. It has not always been easy for me to have open and candid discussions, but the events of 2020 really have been a turning point for me, reminding me that the only way we will truly know and understand each other is by breaking down barriers of fear and discomfort and engaging in these conversations." How have you been supported in your career, and how has it changed you? #BlackHistoryMonth

column30: “Portrait of Edouardo” by Sabl? S. & Sabrina C. Chef Edouardo J. is writing Black History by honoring the recipes of his ancestors at his two Seattle restaurants, Salare Restaurant and JuneBaby. “My grandmother’s food was an iteration of slave food,” says Edouardo J. “The poundcake that I have in my restaurant is the exact same recipe that my grandmother gave me. What makes this poundcake special is when it goes to the table, we get to share that story.” Edouardo J. sees his role as more than a chef, he is an educator and historian. He brings Black Boy Joy to Facebook as he shares everything from new culinary adventures to foraging ingredients in the forest with his son. “The worst thing we can do is create history without understanding history. That’s the biggest thing that I’m teaching my son,” says Edouardo J. “Restaurants are for restoring the soul. I tell the stories of my mom, my grandmother, my uncles and ancestors. It’s appreciating history. Respecting history.” Discover more about Black Boy Joy at https://about.fb.com/community.:=:https://about.fb.com/community/

column30: In celebration of #BlackHistoryMonth, we are featuring team members from our BOND (Black Organization for Networking & Development) employee resource group to discuss what the holiday observance means to them. Learn more about how AmerisourceBergen celebrates individuality and supports inclusion for all. http://ow.ly/drE050DE85O:=:https://www.amerisourcebergen.com/about-us/diversity-and-inclusion “This significance of Black History Month this year is heightened for the very apparent reasons that we have witnessed with VP Kamala Harris, however that is just scratching the surface. Given the multitude and magnitude of instances of social injustice witnessed in the previous year, it has become more important to educate all on the significant contribution of Black Americans in the formation of this country and the world. But unfortunately these events are not new, just more visible. One cannot realize where they are going, or need to go, without understanding the past. This applies to our country. The significance of Black History Month this year, for me, lies in the opportunity to educate and foster understanding for all, hopefully leading to healing for those seeking.”- Kenneth Johnson, Director of Business Relationship Management, D&S Finance & Sourcing IT

column30: No one should have to pick between their health and their budget when it comes to their food. Daily Table was created with a simple goal: to make affordable and healthy food accessible to all. This nonprofit grocer, based in Dorchester, MA, uses donations and surplus products to offer its clients access to healthy food choices, enabling them to take control of their diets and provide for their families. Each month, Daily Table sells 1 million servings of dairy, produce, prepared foods, meat, poultry, fish, and dry goods, and their commissary kitchen prepares 20,000 fresh Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP)-eligible "heat and eat" meals. During the COVID-19 pandemic, Daily Table has been helping those with financial challenges afford healthy food at an average savings of 30%. It also launched a new grocery delivery service that allows immune-suppressed individuals, seniors, and school-age children to get the healthy food they need. As one of our 2021 Champions in Action, Daily Table will receive $35,000 in unrestricted funds and a complimentary membership to the Massachusetts Nonprofit Network. It will also get volunteer, public relations, and promotional support, plus coverage and public service announcements from NECN. The nonprofit is using this funding to support more than 4,000 customers this year. Learn more about Daily Table and our other Champions in Action here: http://spr.ly/6187HcgzZ:=:https://www.citizensbank.com/community/five-non-profit-champions-for-pandemic-relief.aspx?ctzMode=CFG-SOC_FBK_EDT_CTZ_CIADT_DailyTable&WT.mc_id=Citizens-_-FACEBOOK-_-Corporate+Affairs-_--_-21+H1+Champions+in+Action-_-4512217705

column30: Kumar Selvarajan’s impact as an Applications Engineer for our global Seal Auxiliary Systems extends worldwide, well beyond his location in Chennai, India. He works closely with our Commercial Operations team to analyze customer solutions and deliver technical requirements for our seals systems. During his nine years at Flowserve, Kumar has played a key role on several high-profile projects for industry-leading customers. His deep experience as both a Systems Engineer and Applications Engineer has given him special perspective on how to approach his work with innovation. “Innovation can be a simple chart or a complex process design. To me, learning and adapting to new environments is an important part of developing a mindset to do things differently,” he said. Kumar inspires others to develop an innovative mindset through mentoring. He currently mentors a global group of engineers. His goal is to help them build relationships with customers and deliver a great experience in ever-changing markets. “Industries change every day, and Flowserve keeps exploring new ways to be successful. This makes me proud to be a part of this organization,” Kumar said. “Flowserve has a 200-year-old history, but we continue to innovate and grow, and that motivates me every day to deliver my best.” #Flowserve #CareerSpotlight #InnovateWithUs

column30: Because of our geographic reach and scale, HCA Healthcare benefits from comprehensive emergency planning shared across a 180+ hospital system that includes a dedicated enterprise emergency response team and cutting-edge communications technology. Every hospital prepares for worst-case scenarios, and that preparation has saved lives. When disaster strikes, we are there, ready and willing to give our time, expertise and support to help our friends and neighbors. HCA Houston Healthcare North Cypress colleagues brought this to life during last week’s historic winter storm. With many outpatient dialysis facilities forced to close due to the power outages and water shortages, the hospital’s dialysis units ran 24 hours per day. HCA Healthcare dialysis nurse Min Zhao was among the many colleagues who served as a beacon of hope for the influx of dialysis patients at her hospital. HCA Houston Healthcare North Cypress also provided sterile processing of surgical instrumentation for peer hospitals in the region that weren’t able to do their own because of the boil water requirement. To ensure caregivers and hospital staff arrived safely to care for our patients, nearby hotels were provided for colleagues like medical-surgical unit nurses Maria Alcantar and Jamie Craig until the extreme winter weather subsided. Learn more about the Cypress, Texas hospital’s efforts to be the calm before, during and after the storm ? https://bit.ly/3uoaDAg:=:https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/q-a-with-jim-brown-hca-houston-healthcare-north-cypress-provides-stability-during-storm/ar-BB1dRu0d?ocid=entnewsntp #HCAEmergencyOperations #HCAHealthcareStrong

column30: The third person in your tag list owes you one of these for National Margarita Day. ?? Cheers to you both. . ?? Adventure Orange Margarita ?? . Ingredients: ? 1 tbsp. sea salt ? 1 tbsp. chili powder ? 2 1/2 oz. tequila ? 1 1/2 oz. triple sec ? 3 oz. fresh orange juice ? 1 oz. fresh lime juice ? Orange slices . Instructions: Run an orange wedge around the rim of each glass. Dip in the mixture of salt and chili powder. Combine tequila, triple sec, orange juice, and lime juice in a cocktail shaker. Shake well and pour over ice. Garnish with orange slices and enjoy! . To make it a mocktail, swap in lemon-lime soda for the tequila and OJ for the triple sec.

At the time, there weren’t many faces at UPS that looked like Carlton, but he believed that “right is right. It doesn’t matter whom it comes from.” He committed himself to work hard, “give what you’re getting paid for” and helped open the door for other UPSers’ successes. Listen to the podcast below. You’ll never think of doughnuts the same way again. To celebrate #BlackHistoryMonth, we looked to our leaders, past and present, to gain a better understanding of how their challenges and successes shaped their careers and how they shaped, and continue to shape #UPS. column35:
Mark your calendars for 5:30pm on Wednesday, February 24, 2021 (30 Min), for our one-of-a-kind, all-virtual career information session where we'll be defining a new way forward in your career with Branch Careers at Regions within North Central Alabama. 

Attend this event by clicking on the 'Registration link' to be directed to our registration site to register and receive your attendee confirmation email.

Expect a virtual experience packed with can't-miss insights on Why Banking, Why Regions, and the role of Financial Relationship Consultant, presented by Brandon Greve, Consumer Banking Executive for North Central Alabama, and Edward Lubembe, Consumer Banking Manager, that you won't find anywhere else. North Central Alabama includes Birmingham, Anniston, Auburn, Gadsden, Huntsville, Montgomery, Tuscaloosa, and surrounding areas.

Preview of the Financial Relationship Consultant role:
Financial Relationship Consultants are responsible for meeting with customers and prospects to determine financial needs and help reach financial goals. This position offers an exciting opportunity for candidates with retail or sales experience that are interested in beginning a career with opportunities for growth, development and upward mobility.

Regions is now hiring Financial Relationship Consultants as well as additional positions within the branch if you are interested in joining our team before or after our virtual event. To match your skills to our open positions in your area, visit www.regions.com/careers:=:https://www.regions.com/about-regions/careers to apply. You can filter positions by the Job Category of "Consumer - Retail Banking Group," and Distance Within Postal Code or State. Following your application, you will automatically receive an email from our vendor with a link to complete an online assessment within 5 days to be considered for the position. Please be sure to check your spam or junk mailbox if it was not delivered to your inbox.

column35: Exactly one week ago, Travelers Insurance and the Travelers Championship announced their extraordinary $1 million match to help inspire community support for our rebuilding efforts after the fire. Today, we are excited to share that THE MATCH HAS BEEN MET and thanks to the additional and exceptional $1 million commitment from Newman's Own Foundation, we feel we now have the anticipated funds needed to rebuild the structures that were lost to best meet the current, future and varied needs of the children we serve. We are deeply grateful for the tremendous outpouring of kindness and generosity from the thousands of people in our Camp family and beyond who brought us to this milestone. To the more than 3,300 people who donated, every camper family that raised money on social media and everyone who reached out with their prayers and well wishes, know that we are honored by your friendship. Heartfelt thanks to our friends Travelers, the Travelers Championship and to Newman’s Own Foundation. Because of them – and all of you – we can now focus our efforts on rebuilding!

column30: Ever wondered what it’s like to drive around a rocket? Our Mechanical Engineer, Breanne, is 1? of just a few women to ever drive NASA's Kennedy Space Center’s Crawler-Transporter 2, which has the important job of carrying spacecraft and rocket systems to the launch pad. And at 6 million pounds and large enough to fit a ? diamond on top, maneuvering this critical piece of equipment is no simple task. “It’s awesome being a part of the Artemis program,” Breanne says. “Being out here has always been a dream of mine, and it’s exciting to have that dream turn into reality at such a historic time for NASA - National Aeronautics and Space Administration” Breanne is part of the space center’s younger workforce – the Artemis generation – preparing to expand human exploration to the Moon and on to Mars. http://jcob.co/FCF650DEybr:=:https://www.jacobs.com/newsroom/news/celebrating-engineers-week-2021-jacobs-teammates-challenging-today-reinventing?utm_source=social&utm_medium=facebook&utm_term=f3b656d4-edc5-412d-bb78-78c659fa2dd4&utm_content=&utm_campaign=news-release #EWeek2021

column6: Above all else, we are committed to the care and improvement of human life. In recognition of this commitment, we strive to deliver high quality, cost effective healthcare in the communities we serve.
column30: Throughout #BlackHistoryMonth, we’re recognizing influential leaders across HCA Healthcare for leading the charge to promote health and well-being for all Americans. Leaders who’ve contributed to the strength and vibrancy of the communities they serve. Leaders like Jyric Sims, chief executive officer at HCA Healthcare’s Medical City Fort Worth in Texas. Jyric, a first generation high school and college graduate, credits his parents for teaching him lessons of ”authenticity, hard work, discipline, dedication, a sense of belonging, and that to whom much is given, much is expected." With a strong sense of duty and in an effort to lead change, Jyric also mentors Black undergraduate and graduate students who aspire to be leaders in healthcare. "I make time to mentor them because it is my rent that I pay while occupying this space right now," said Jyric. Leading by example is just one of many reasons he was recently named amongst “70 African American leaders in healthcare to know” by Becker's Hospital Review. Thank you, Jyric, for positively influencing healthcare delivery in the Dallas-Fort Worth area and for advocating for the next generation of African American leaders. #PositiveImpact #BlackHistoryMonth

column30: We are pleased to announce that we have entered into an agreement to acquire People’s United Financial, a diversified, community-focused financial services company. At M&T, we believe our value lies in providing our customers the capabilities of a large bank with the engagement model of a localized, community-based organization. Founded in 1842, in People’s United we have found a partner with an equally long history of serving all their communities with commercial, retail banking and wealth management solutions throughout its network. “Combining our common legacies and our complementary footprints will strengthen our ability to serve our communities and customers and provide solutions that make a difference in people’s lives. I am incredibly excited about this opportunity and look forward to welcoming new customers and team members to our M&T family.” -- René Jones, chairman and chief executive officer of M&T Bank Corporation. The acquisition is expected to close in the fourth quarter of 2021. We are committed to keeping you informed of ongoing updates. Please visit our website to learn more and other important information: https://www.mtb.com/peoples-united:=:https://www3.mtb.com/peoples-united

column30: Dr. Daniel Hale Williams founded the Provident Hospital in Chicago, the first hospital with a racially integrated staff. column30: Since going public in 2005 under $NDAQ, Nasdaq has gone from being strictly a market provider to something more impactful. "We were a player and had developed our own identity within the industry, but needed independence to fully realize it,” recalled CEO Adena Friedman. In 2001, Nasdaq filed its official application to register as an independent national securities exchange with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), and about a year later, the SEC formally approved Nasdaq’s application to become a registered national securities exchange, which allowed Nasdaq to begin operations as a self-regulatory organization and fully divest itself from the NASD’s control. At long last, Nasdaq was an independent, shareholder-owned company with the freedom to realize its full potential within the financial industry. Learn more as we celebrate #Nasdaq50: nasdaq50.com

Two special guests will join us tomorrow 2/22 in an engaging conversation designed to honor and celebrate the life of Malcolm X, starting at 6:30 pm ET: https://mtblackhistorymonthseries.splashthat.com Anna Malaika Tubbs will shine a light on Black motherhood by telling the story of the three extraordinary women who raised and shaped some of America's most pivotal heroes: Martin Luther King, Jr., Malcolm X, and James Baldwin. Through his biography Black Minded: The Political Philosophy of Malcolm X, Michael Sawyer will examine Malcom X’s philosophical system, exploring themes of ontology, the body, geographic space and revolution. #SchomburgCenter #BlackHistoryMonth

column30: If you are hauling trash for pickup, please be aware of where your natural gas meter is located. As debris is put out for heavy trash pickup, make sure it is placed away from the meter. In many areas the meter may be located near the curb. If debris is near a gas meter, the mechanized equipment used by trash collectors could pull up the meter, damaging it and causing a potentially hazardous situation. If this happens, leave the area immediately and call 911 and CenterPoint at 713-659-2111.

column30: “Ask no more from your team than you would expect from yourself – physically, mentally and emotionally. That requires you to really learn what motivates your teams and your leaders, and what motivates your own people. You need to know who they are.” – Bill Duttweiler, Raymond James Cyber Threat Analyst and Marine Corps Combat Veteran Today, Raymond James executives and armed forces veterans shared their experiences and thoughts on military leadership as it relates to the corporate world. The panelists, Mike Edwards, Bill Duttweiler, Alicia Laguerre and Ed Sudzina, talked about several characteristics that have easily translated from the military to their civilian careers, including the need to communicate clearly, advocate for your team members, prioritize goals and adapt to any situation. They also advised associates on how they can deepen their understanding of leadership to aid in their professional development and growth. Thank you to our Veterans Inclusion Network, Valor, for hosting this educational event. #RJCulture

column30: If your pipes are frozen, there are steps you can take to help prevent water damage: ? Locate and close the main water shutoff valve as soon as possible before temps rise above freezing. ? Inspect pipes for damage, including those in attics and crawl spaces, where it is safe to do so. ? As temps increase above freezing, watch and listen for signs of water leaks. ? If a pipe is leaking, do not turn on the main water valve. Open all faucets including those outside to drain remaining water and call a licensed plumber.

column30: Driven by his deep passion for social justice, Alex Wright founded the African Heritage Food Co-op in 2016 to make a positive impact in his community. Rooted in his fundamental belief that togetherness, unity, and collaboration lift Black communities into prosperity, the co-op allows for Alex and his community to share in the ownership while working together to lift families out of poverty. The community garden is locally based, keeping money within the community and creating an opportunity to keep resources in the local economy. Employees can walk to work, and fresh healthy food is now available, where it wasn’t previously so readily on hand. #CelebratingCustomers #CommunityBank
